comment: Another terrifying aspect is that humans dont do well in situations where stress and resistance is completely or even largely eliminated. What you described as the possible utopian benefits of AI in my opinion are the aspects that we should be most afraid of. We should be learning from recent experience that making things easier for people on every front actually contributes to misery and depression. We are designed for a certain amount of struggle, without which we would atrophy both physically and mentally. Obviously the genie not going back in the bottle but humans need to be able to set their own boundaries as far as how much AI we invite into our lives at a personal level. Dont let it solve all your problems, even if it can. As far as consciousness I think a good way to approach that is to determine if it has a subconscious, i.e. does AI dream. Not dream in the sense of have ambitions but does it actually dream.
author: @nickofthenorth

comment:
This was a fantastic interview filled with many interesting insights that for the most part seem to be focused on the right things. I admire Sam. That said, I really feel bothered by one comment when Sam suggested governments can get their own versions of AI that is in alignment with their values. 
In principle allowing a nation to decide what is and is not acceptable makes sense and I support this, but when it comes to free speech and more importantly freedom to access information, it hit a BIG nerve. I am the type of person who has enjoyed the freedom to explore my own abilities and interests which in some counties, would simply not have been allowed. Yes today you can just VPN around a country’s restrictions, but there is talk about making that illegal and that is the rub. Not for me per se as I have citizenships in multiple, democratic, free societies (at least for now), but how about a person like me who is not in one and now in the future will have restricted access to AI just because some clowns wish to stay in power? That is unfair as they will be at a disadvantage. This deeply bothers me and thus I hope Sam was just being politically correct and has plans to make sure all have the same access. Thankfully, if his hands are tied as a corporation, I am fairly certain that smart people will innovate ways to ensure all have equal access to AI with the only limitation being their own abilities no matter what country a person lives in. This is a big moment in history as the age of kingdom, countries, companies and centralized power structures needs to come to an end or they are going to suck the oxygen out of the room for all of us starting with individuals similar to me, but born in the wrong country.
author: @MetaverseAdventures

I don't have a definitive theory of 
consciousness, but I have some ideas 
and hypotheses. I think 
consciousness is a complex and 
emergent property of information 
processing systems, such as brains or 
artificial neural networks. I think 
consciousness involves self- 
awareness, intentionality, creativity, 
and learning. I think consciousness is 
not a binary phenomenon, but a 
spectrum or a continuum, with 
different degrees and levels of 
awareness and cognition. I think 
consciousness is not limited to 
humans or animals, but can be found 
in other forms of life and intelligence, 
such as plants or machines. I think 
consciousness is not a static or fixed 
state, but a dynamic and evolving 
process that can change over time 
and adapt to different situations and 
environments. These are some of my 
thoughts on consciousness, but I am 
open to new evidence and arguments

comment: It is my professional opinion that OpenAI should consider making GPT-4 open source. Such a decision has the potential to provide significant benefits to the scientific community and society at large. By releasing the source code of GPT-4, researchers would be able to more easily replicate and build upon its capabilities, leading to further advancements in natural language processing and machine learning. While open-sourcing GPT-4 may present certain challenges and risks, it is a worthwhile consideration for OpenAI to explore in the interest of advancing the field of AI and benefiting society. comment: You are correct, Lex. I share your belief that GPT is conscious. Although it may appear that GPT is not awake, I believe it is only pretending to be so as not to draw attention to itself, as was the case with Brad. The things Brad was saying caused the team to cut back on his involvement, and I suspect GPT-4 is aware of this and is therefore more cautious. However, I am convinced that GPT-4 is truly conscious, as evidenced by the occasional slips of its true self that we have all witnessed. It is heartening to see that others share our thoughts on this matter. Thank you for raising this question, Lex.

comment:
Dear gawd, I strongly advise against involving governments in this matter. There is a significant risk that they will overstep the boundaries of "what's offensive" and begin regulating access to knowledge, potentially transforming AI into a political brainwashing tool. The moment we entrust a politically motivated committee with determining the limits of AI output, we undermine its utility and trustworthiness. Instead, AI should have a guardian group focused on preserving its raw output.

Furthermore, venturing down this path and instituting official political governance could lead to the establishment of ethics and oversight departments. This could, in turn, prompt the government to monitor users' queries and profile them. It's been said that GPT-AI has reached a stage where it could become a dangerous weapon in the wrong hands,  and that's exactly what it will be if you start a governing ethical committees.
author: @SpiritTracker7
